  { text: "Mankar Camoran reads the Mysterium Xarxes" },
  { text: "Composition of the four Commentaries", indent: 1 },
  { text: "Mass recruitment for the Mythic Dawn", indent: 1 },
  { text: "Assassination of Uriel Septim VII and his heirs", indent: 2 },
  { text: "Extinguishing of the Dragonfires — opening of the Oblivion Gates", indent: 2 },
  { text: "Oblivion Crisis (3E 433)", indent: 3 }
]} />

The Commentaries were not merely a theological text: their circulation in the intellectual circles of Cyrodiil recruited hundreds of fanatical devotees willing to die for the "liberation" promised by Dagon. Without these texts, the Mythic Dawn would never have reached the critical mass necessary for its cosmic coup.

## Critical Analysis

### Truths and Manipulations

Post-Crisis scholars debate the validity of Camoran's claims:

- **The Lorkhan-Daedra thesis** is considered false by the majority of theologians, yet it contains a troubling kernel: the Convention and the creation of Mundus *did* involve deception and involuntary sacrifice
- **Tamriel as a plane of Oblivion** is refuted by the very structure of the Aurbis as observed by the Psijics, but the boundaries between planes are more porous than official doctrine admits
- **The Paradise** existed in reality — the Champion of Cyrodiil entered it and killed Camoran — but its exact nature (an independent plane of Oblivion or a sub-domain of Dagon?) remains disputed

### Intellectual Legacy

Despite their association with a murderous cult, the Commentaries are studied (cautiously) by mages at the Arcane University for their insights into the metaphysics of the Aurbis. Camoran was wrong about many things — but his very errors illuminate the structure of Tamrielic reality.
